    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Hospices Civils de Lyon</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Stage IIIA non-small cell lung cancers comprising a mediastinal ganglionic invasion N2
      account for 20 to 30% of the NSCLCs. They are almost always potentially resectable, but the
      results obtained by surgery alone or surgery followed by chemotherapy (CT) and/or
      radiotherapy (RT) are insufficient. The neoadjuvant approach was tested, in randomized tests
      of exclusive CT, or in noncomparative tests of RT-CT.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      These results justify the choice of the study design currently suggested, testing the
      preoperative feasibility

        1. chemotherapy: cisplatin-Gemzar (arm A) or

        2. chemoradiotherapy: cisplatin-navelbine-radiotherapy (arm B) or
           Carboplatin-Taxol-radiotherapy (arm C).

      The results obtained, in terms of feasibility and toxicity, will make it possible to select
      the optimal diagrams for a phase III study.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
